🟢 Builder Design Pattern — Complete Notes
🧠 1️⃣ Definition

Builder Pattern is used to construct complex objects step-by-step, providing better readability and flexibility compared to constructors with many parameters.

🎯 2️⃣ Problem It Solves
❌ Telescoping Constructor Problem
User user = new User("John", 25, "Bangalore", "123456", true);

Problems:

Hard to read ❌

Order confusion ❌

Optional fields messy ❌

❌ Setters Approach
User user = new User();
user.setName("John");
user.setAge(25);

Problems:

Mutable object ❌

Incomplete state possible ❌

✅ 3️⃣ Builder Solution
User user = new User.UserBuilder()
                    .setName("John")
                    .setAge(25)
                    .setCity("Bangalore")
                    .build();

✔ Readable
✔ Flexible
✔ Safe
✔ Supports immutability

🧱 4️⃣ Structure
Class
class User {

    private String name;
    private int age;
    private String city;

    private User(UserBuilder builder) {
        this.name = builder.name;
        this.age = builder.age;
        this.city = builder.city;
    }
Builder Class
    public static class UserBuilder {

        private String name;
        private int age;
        private String city;

        public UserBuilder setName(String name) {
            this.name = name;
            return this;
        }

        public UserBuilder setAge(int age) {
            this.age = age;
            return this;
        }

        public UserBuilder setCity(String city) {
            this.city = city;
            return this;
        }

        public User build() {
            return new User(this);
        }
    }
}
🔑 5️⃣ Core Concepts
✅ 1. Method Chaining
builder.setName("John").setAge(25).setCity("Bangalore");

👉 Works because:

Each method returns the SAME builder object
✅ 2. Why return this
public UserBuilder setName(String name) {
    this.name = name;
    return this;
}

👉 this = current builder object

✔ Enables chaining
✔ Keeps modifying same object

✅ 3. Step-by-Step Construction
UserBuilder builder = new UserBuilder();

builder.setName("John");   // step 1
builder.setAge(25);        // step 2
builder.setCity("BLR");    // step 3

User user = builder.build(); // final object
🧠 Internal Flow
Builder (mutable, keeps updating)
        ↓
build()
        ↓
Final Object (immutable)
🎯 6️⃣ Key Insight
Builder = temporary object storing values

build() = creates final object using those values
🔥 7️⃣ Advantages

✔ Readable object creation
✔ No constructor confusion
✔ Supports optional fields
✔ Enables immutability
✔ Flexible (can build conditionally)

⚠️ 8️⃣ When to Use

Use Builder when:

Many fields (especially optional)

Object creation is complex

You want immutable objects

You want clean and readable code

🚫 9️⃣ When NOT to Use

Simple objects (2–3 fields)

No optional fields

No complexity

